@node features "Features"

                               Features

-Simple installation: just run the game and play!

-S_Tiles is a "Workbench" game, so it is meant to be played on the
 Workbench screen. The game window can be resized up to a maximum of
 640 x 400 pixels, and the game is redisplayed according to the new
 window size. If the window is too small, it will automatically be
 resized to an adequate displayable size.

-You can play the game with the mouse or with the cursor keys of the
 keyboard.

-As the game uses as little of the computer's ressources as possible,
 you can run other applications, games, etc. at the same time.

-S_Tiles works on all Amigas with Workbench 1.3 or higher.

@endnode

@node histo "History"

                               Versions History

  What follows are the various updates that were done since the first
version of this game.

1.0: -First public release.

1.01-1.04: -Various unreleased versions.

1.05: -No more blitting operations, just simple drawings, it's more friendly
       for blitter handicapped systems (Pegasos/Morphos, Amithlon, etc.)...
       and the display updates (when the game starts or if you resize the
       window) are faster.
      -Some cosmetic changes were made: the pull-down menus were changed, as
       well as the game buttons.

1.06: -Bugfix: The game could crash if it was run on a Workbench lower than
       2.0.
      -Various changes were made to the game code.

1.07: -Various changes have been made to the program code:
        -The routine to generate the main game window has been revised.
        -Now the game window can be resized to a 640 x 400 pixel size.
        -Some variables have been redefined in the unlikely, but not
         impossible, case that they could overflow, causing the program to
         crash.
        -Some unneeded code have been removed.
        -Some cosmetic changes have been made; the numbers from 1 to 15 have
         been redrawn.

1.08: -Now the game tiles can be moved by using the cursor keys.
      -Various changes have been made to the program code.

1.1: -Now, if the Workbench has 8 colours or more, the numbers are drawn in
      colour.
     -When the game is completed, if the number of moves exceeds 9999 (!),
      the game displays 'many moves', instead of the real number of moves.
     -The 'About' routine has been revised.
     -A correction has been made in the French instructions concerning the
      installation of the game: originally it stated that the Workbench
      needed to have at least 8 colours, when in english, no such thing was
      stated... So, to clear things up: it is NOT necessary to have an 8
      colour Workbench to run this game. I am sorry for any confusion this
      may have caused...
     -Various other improvements have been made.

@endnode

@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "S_Tiles" where you want
on your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files or
Libraries are needed.

                             How to play?

  The game consists of 15 tiles, numbered from 1 to 15, that were
randomly shuffled. You have to place these tiles in the right order
(starting with the lower numbers at the top and the higher numbers
on the lower tiles), in the least number of moves possible.

  Playing with S_Tiles is very simple: just click on one of the
arrows, each of these arrows will move a tile in that direction,
where the empty space was located. Note that the arrows will always
follow the empty space, as they will move to the same column and row
where the empty space is located. You can also use the cursor keys
to move the tiles (by pressing a cursor key, a tile will move in the
corresponding direction towards the empty space). 

  If a tile is located on the edge of the board and the empty space
is on the other side and you click on an arrow (or the corresponding
cursor key) that would move that tile off the edge, it will
'wrap-around' and go where the empty space was located.

  You can restart a game any time by clicking on the 'New Game'
button (or with Right-Amiga + 'N' keys on the keyboard).

  Have fun!

@endnode

